<br>
I don't even know how to plan my game now.  T-Rod was the way for the high end raiding plan and unfortunately I dumped 9 AA's into quick summoning just to do faster coh's and mod rods.  Maybe they will up the casting mastery AA percentages and mana use.  I also want to wait and see what type of item is being summoned.  If it's an item thats summoned per target and then target just clicks when used if time is available then that won't be too bad.  /rt won't be bad either if need be, but will the timer be a buff, how will one know when its time to get another hit off the pipe.<br>
<br>
I also laugh at all the whiner mages that complained and feedbacked this since rods became part of high end encounters.  And now that this is diminishing they whine more that mages are getting nerfed.  I agree it was overpowering/unbalanced.  It also makes it useless for mages to go for Rune items - SoA's/HP Halo's when you have to wait 60 secs for a hit.  As far as soloing purposes, 3 hits off a SoA and summoning the rod and clicking was about 30 secs anyway.  This would give anywhere of a minimum of 260 mana netted so a minimum of 520 mana every 60 secs.  Now add specializations and Casting Mastery AA skills, you gain a lot more, say 200 mana netted for 2 rods = 720.  So the new item is like half that 360 mana for 450 hp and whats the mana cost going to be for it so T-Rods will no longer be the tool for soloing.<br>
<br>
One proposal is to keep the old spell for mages and make the rod no drop.  That way mages can still have an advantage for runes and regen.  It also allows the mage to upkeep his mana to summon the 60 sec rods for those who need if /rt needs to be implemented.  What will happen?  who knows....  Whatever mages gain or haven't seen won't happen until the next expansion if there is one after PoP. <br>
<br>
So far, the only changes on test I have heard confirmed are the manaburn and cleric changes.  I haven't seen anything about T-Rods changing yet on test, they are still the way they are.<br>
